{{other uses|Jimmy James (disambiguation){{!}}Jimmy James}}
{{Use Australian English|date=October 2018}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}
'''Jimmy James''' [[Medal of the Order of Australia|OAM]] (1913–91)<ref name="Holmes2003p66DOB">{{Harvnb|Holmes|2003|p=66}}. While Jimmy James' birthdate was not officially recorded, he claimed that he had been born in 1913.</ref> was an [[Indigenous Australian|Aboriginal Australian]] and member of the [[Pitjantjatjara people|Pitjantjatjara]] people, who was best known as an [[Aboriginal tracker]] who helped [[South Australia Police|South Australian Police]] in tracking criminals over a forty-year period.

Born near [[Ernabella]] (now Pukatja) in central Australia to his parents, Warlawurru and Kaarnka, he spent his late childhood at the [[Ooldea, South Australia|Ooldea Mission]]. He left the area in 1945, after being wrongfully arrested, and headed to the [[South Australia]]n [[Riverland]], where he assisted in the establishment of the [[Gerard (Aboriginal Council)|Gerard Mission]]. It was there that he married Lilian Disher in 1947. In 1948, James began his career as a tracker for police and landowners, and gained much of his reputation tracking criminals (including arsonists, poachers and escapees) and lost persons. His successes including tracking escapee James Smith and finding Wendy Pfeiffer (who was nine years old at the time) after she was abducted near [[Mylor, South Australia|Mylor]].<ref name="Holmes2003p66">{{Harvnb|Holmes|2003|p=66}}</ref>

Jimmy James was awarded the [[Medal of the Order of Australia]] in 1984 and the inaugural South Australian Aboriginal Person of the Year in 1983, and he was given a gold medallion by the family of Wendy Pfeiffer.<ref name="Holmes2003p66" /><ref name="SundayMail2007">{{Harvnb|"Police halt medals auction"|24 June 2007}}</ref> After his death, a memorial to Jimmy James was erected in [[Berri, South Australia#Art and culture|Berri, South Australia]].<ref name="BerriTheAge">{{Harvnb|"Berri"|8 February 2004}}</ref>

